{"title_page": "Koningsdag", "text_new": "{{redirect|Queen's Day}}\n{{for|the Belgian Kings day|King's Feast}}\n{{short description|Dutch national holiday}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name = ''Koningsdag''\n|type         = national\n|longtype     = [[Public holiday|National holiday]]\n|image        = Amsterdam's Canals.jpg\n|caption      = People dressed in orange on the [[canals of Amsterdam]] in 2010\n|observedby   = [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] ([[Netherlands]], [[Aruba]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Sint&nbsp;Maarten]])\n|date         = 27 April (26 April if 27 April is a Sunday)\n|celebrations = Partying, [[Oranjegekte|wearing orange]] costumes, [[flea market]]s, concerts and traditional local gatherings\n|significance = Birthday of [[King Willem-Alexander]]\n|duration     = 1 day\n|frequency    = annual\n}}\n\n'''''Koningsdag''''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8ko\u02d0n\u026a\u014bzd\u0251x|-|Nl-Koningsdag.ogg}}) or '''King's Day''' is a [[public holiday|national holiday]] in the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]]. Celebrated on 27 April (26 April if the 27th is a Sunday), the date marks the birth of [[King Willem-Alexander]].<ref name=\"BWBR0032908\">{{cite journal|url=http://wetten.overheid.nl/BWBR0032908/geldigheidsdatum_01-01-2014|title=Besluit vaststelling en aanduiding zevenentwintigste april als Koningsdag|id=BWBR0032908|language=nl|date=30 April 2013|authorlink=Ministry of General Affairs|author=AZ}}</ref> Until the [[abdication]] of [[Queen Beatrix]] in 2013, the holiday was known as '''''Koninginnedag''''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02ccko\u02d0n\u026a\u014b\u02c8\u026an\u0259d\u0251x|-|Nl-koninginnedag.ogg}}) or '''Queen's Day''' and was celebrated on 30 April.\n\nThe holiday was initially observed on 31 August 1885 as ''Prinsessedag'' or Princess's Day, the fifth birthday of [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Princess Wilhelmina]], then [[heir presumptive]] to the Dutch throne. On her accession in November 1890 the holiday acquired the name ''Koninginnedag'', first celebrated on 31 August 1891. In September 1948, Wilhelmina's daughter [[Juliana of the Netherlands|Juliana]] ascended to the throne and the holiday was moved to her birthday, 30 April. The holiday was celebrated on this date from 1949.\n\nJuliana's daughter, Beatrix, retained the celebration on 30 April after she ascended the throne in 1980, though her birthday was on 31 January.<ref name=\"BWBR0031338\">{{cite journal|url=http://wetten.overheid.nl/BWBR0031338/geldigheidsdatum_01-05-2002|title=Besluit aanduiding van de dertigste april als Koninginnedag|id=BWBR0031338|language=nl|date=24 April 1980|authorlink=Ministry of General Affairs|author=AZ}}</ref> Beatrix altered her mother's custom of receiving a floral parade at [[Soestdijk Palace]], instead choosing to visit different Dutch towns each year and join in the festivities with her children.\n\nIn 2009, the Queen was celebrating Queen's Day in the city of [[Apeldoorn]] when [[2009 attack on the Dutch royal family|a man attempted to attack her]] by trying to ram the royal family's bus with his car; instead he drove into a crowd of people and crashed into a monument: seven people in the crowd were killed, as was the driver.\n\nQueen Beatrix abdicated on ''Koninginnedag'' 2013, and her son, Willem-Alexander, ascended the throne (the first king since the observance of the national holiday). As a result, the holiday became known as ''Koningsdag'' from 2014 on, and the celebration was shifted three days backwards to 27 April, the King's birthday.\n\n''Koningsdag'' is known for its nationwide ''vrijmarkt'' (\"free market\"), at which the Dutch sell their used items. It is also an opportunity for \"orange madness\" or ''[[oranjegekte]]'', a kind of frenzy named for the national colour.\n\n==History==\n===Wilhelmina (1885\u20131948)===\n[[File:Oranjefeestvreugde in Amsterdam.ogv|thumb|thumbtime=3|right|''Koninginnedag'' on 31 August 1932 in Amsterdam]]\n\nFaced with an unpopular monarchy, in the 1880s the [[Liberal Union (Netherlands)|liberals]] in Dutch government sought a means of promoting national unity.<ref name=\"nu\" /> King [[William III of the Netherlands|William III]] was disliked, but his four-year-old daughter [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Princess Wilhelmina]] was not.<ref name=\"mag\" /> A holiday honouring King William had been intermittently held on his birthday, and J. W. R. Gerlach, editor of the newspaper ''Utrechts Provinciaal en Stedelijk Dagblad'', proposed that the princess's birthday be observed as an opportunity for patriotic celebration and national reconciliation.<ref name=\"dag\">{{Cite book\n  | last =Deploige\n  | first = Jeroen\n  |author2=Gita Deneckere\n   | title = Mystifying the Monarch: Studies on Discourse, Power, and History\n  | publisher = Amsterdam University Press\n  | location = Amsterdam\n  | year =2006\n  | page = 187\n  | isbn = 90-5356-767-4\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=OLHNKiSKvBwC&dq=Prinsessedag&source=gbs_navlinks_s\n  | accessdate = 6 May 2011 }}</ref> ''Prinsessedag'' or Princess's Day was first celebrated in the Netherlands on 31 August 1885, Wilhelmina's fifth birthday. The young princess was paraded through the streets, waving to the crowds.<ref name=\"mag\" /> The first observance occurred only in [[Utrecht]], but other municipalities quickly began to observe it, organizing activities for children.<ref name=\"dag\" /> Further processions were held in the following years, and when Wilhelmina inherited the throne in 1890, ''Prinsessedag'' was renamed ''Koninginnedag'', or Queen's Day.<ref name=\"mag\" /> By then almost every Dutch town and city was marking the holiday.<ref name=\"dag\" />\n\nThe celebration proved popular, and when the Queen came of age in 1898, her inauguration was postponed a week to 6 September so as not to interfere with ''Koninginnedag''.<ref name=\"plan\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Chadwick\n  | first = Nicola\n  | title = Planning the perfect Queen's Day\n  | publisher = Radio Netherlands Worldwide\n  | date = 27 April 2011\n  | url = http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/planning-perfect-queens-day\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110430040355/http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/planning-perfect-queens-day\n  | archive-date = 30 April 2011\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref> The annual holiday fell on the final day of school [[summer vacation]], which made it popular among schoolchildren.<ref name=\"mag\">{{Cite journal\n |last        = Peek\n |first       = Mike\n |title       = Long live the Queen\n |journal     = Amsterdam Magazine\n |pages       = 29\u201333\n |date        = April 2011\n |url         = http://amsterdam-magazine.com/2011/04/feature-long-life-the-queen/\n |accessdate  = 30 April 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110811112446/http://amsterdam-magazine.com/2011/04/feature-long-life-the-queen/\n |archivedate = 11 August 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> It is uncertain how much Wilhelmina enjoyed the festivities; although writer Mike Peek, in a 2011 magazine article about ''Koninginnedag'', suggests she was enthusiastic,<ref name=\"mag\" /> there is a story of Wilhelmina, after a tired return from one of these birthday processions, making her doll bow until the toy's hair was dishevelled, and telling it, \"Now you shall sit in a carriage and bow until your back aches, and see how much you like being a Queen!\"<ref>{{Cite journal\n  | last = Bates\n  | first = Winslow\n  | title = The girl queen and her coronation\n  | journal = National Magazine\n  | pages = 12\u201318\n  | date = October 1898\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oYzNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA17\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n''Koninginnedag'' 1902 not only honoured the Queen's birthday, but was celebrated with increased enthusiasm as it marked her recovery from serious illness.<ref name=\"nu\">{{cite web\n |title=The Queen's official birthday (Koninginnedag) \n |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] \n |url=http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/globale-paginas/taalrubrieken/english/monarchy/the-queens-official-birthday-(koninginnedag)/ \n |accessdate=30 April 2012 \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506033422/http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/globale-paginas/taalrubrieken/english/monarchy/the-queens-official-birthday-%28koninginnedag%29 \n |archive-date= 6 May 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> Wilhelmina rarely attended ''Koninginnedag'' festivities after reaching adulthood.<ref name=\"old\" /> She attended ceremonies for her silver jubilee in 1923, which included massive festivities in Amsterdam and [[The Hague]], despite the Queen's request that large sums not be spent because economic conditions at the time were difficult. To ensure that even the poorer parts of the city were included, bands played simultaneously at 28&nbsp;locations across The Hague.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news\n  | title = Holland preparing for Queen's jubilee\n  | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10A16F9345416738DDDA00894DF405B838EF1D3\n  | newspaper =[[The New York Times]]\n  | date = 9 July 1923\n  |page = 13\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Wilhelmina made further exceptions for such events as her fiftieth birthday in 1930.<ref name=\"old\">{{cite news\n |title       = Queen's Day history dates back to 1889\n |url         = http://www.nisnews.nl/dossiers/royal_house/260401_922.htm\n |publisher   = NIS News\n |date        = 26 April 2001\n |accessdate  = 1 May 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930192138/http://www.nisnews.nl/dossiers/royal_house/260401_922.htm\n |archivedate = 30 September 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> During the [[German occupation of the Netherlands]] during World War II, ''Koninginnedag'' celebrations were banned, and members of the Orange Committees, which organize the holiday events, destroyed their records for fear of German reprisals.<ref name=\"plan\" />\n\n===Juliana (1948\u20131980)===\n[[File:Arnhem Parade 30 april B.jpg|thumb|thumbtime=3|thumb|right|Military parade in [[Arnhem]], ''Koninginnedag'' 1958]]\nAnother summertime birthday celebration in the Netherlands was that of Wilhelmina's mother, [[Emma of the Netherlands|Queen-Regent Emma]], who after Wilhelmina attained adulthood generally spent her own birthday, 2 August, at [[Soestdijk Palace]] in [[Baarn]]. Until her death in 1934, Emma received [[Bloemencorso|an annual floral tribute]] from the townsfolk on her birthday. In 1937 Wilhelmina's daughter and heiress, [[Juliana of the Netherlands|Princess Juliana]], took up residence at Soestdijk Palace following her marriage, and the townsfolk made their floral presentation to her, moving the date to Juliana's birthday, 30 April.<ref name=\"old\" /> In September 1948 Juliana ascended to the Dutch throne and from 1949 onwards ''Koninginnedag'' was on her birthday.<ref name=\"man\">{{cite news\n  | title = Queen's Day of Netherlands April 30, 2011\n  | url = http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/316226/queens-day-netherlands-april-30-2011\n  | periodical = Manila Bulletin\n  | date = 30 April 2011\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> The change in date attracted immediate approval from Dutch children, who gained an extra day of holiday. The first observance of the holiday on the new date included a huge circus at the [[Olympic Stadium (Amsterdam)|Amsterdam Olympic Stadium]]\u2014one not attended by the royal family, who remained at Soestdijk Palace.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schorr|first=Danel L.\n  | title = Dutch queen guides nations through crises, eyes first anniversary\n  | url = https://secure.pqarchiver.com/csmonitor_historic/access/171767732.html?FMT=AI&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+16%2C+1949&author=By+Daniel+L.+Schorr+Special+Correspondent+of+The+Christian+Science+Monitor&pub=Christian+Science+Monitor&desc=Dutch+Queen+Guides+Nation+Through+Crises%2C+Eyes+First+Anniversary\n  | periodical = [[The Christian Science Monitor]]\n  | date = 16 April 1949\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Queen Juliana retained the floral tribute, staying each year on ''Koninginnedag'' at Soestdijk Palace to receive it. The parade became televised in the 1950s, and ''Koninginnedag'' increasingly became a national holiday, with workers given the day off.<ref name=\"nu\" /> Juliana had a reputation as a \"queen of the people\", and according to Peek, \"it felt as if she invited her subjects to the royal home\".<ref name=\"mag\" />\n\nIn early 1966 Juliana's eldest daughter, Princess Beatrix, married [[Prince Claus of the Netherlands|Klaus-Georg von Amsberg]]. The marriage was controversial because the new Prince Claus (as he was dubbed) was a German, and Claus himself had served in the [[Wehrmacht|German Army]] during the war.  Anti-German riots in Amsterdam marred the wedding day and the following observances of ''Koninginnedag''. Fearing further demonstrations on the holiday, government officials decided to open Amsterdam city centre to the ''vrijmarkt'' (\"free market\") that had long been held on ''Koninginnedag'' in the outskirts of town, principally for children. The ''vrijmarkt'' occupied the space where demonstrations might have been held, and began a new custom.<ref name=\"mag\" />\n\n===Beatrix (1980\u20132013)===\n[[File:Beatrixscheveningen2005.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Queen Beatrix]] speaks with the mayor of [[The Hague]], [[Wim Deetman]] in [[Scheveningen]], ''Koninginnedag'' 2005.]]\nWhen [[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Queen Beatrix]] succeeded her mother Juliana on the latter's abdication on 30 April 1980, the new queen decided to keep the holiday on 30 April as a tribute to her mother.<ref name=\"BWBR0031338\"/><ref name=\"nu\"/> (If 30 April fell on a Sunday, ''Koninginnedag'' was observed the previous day\u2014this occurred most recently in 2006.<ref name=\"joel\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Romanko\n  | first = J.R.\n  | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE7D91031F93AA25750C0A9609C8B63&scp=8&sq=queen's%20Day%20Netherlands&st=cse\n  | periodical = [[The New York Times]]\n  | date = 19 March 2006\n  | title =Datebook\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>) The reason was practical as well\u2014Beatrix's actual birthday on 31 January would have been less conducive to the traditional outdoor activities.<ref name=\"man\" /> Rather than remaining at the palace and letting the Dutch people come to her, Beatrix instead usually visited two towns each year for ''Koninginnedag'' celebrations.<ref name=\"nu\" /> Local crafts and customs were demonstrated for the royal family, who had the opportunity to join in.<ref name=\"nick\" /><ref>{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.expatcentreleiden.nl/news/news_item/t/queen_s_day\n |publisher   = Expat Centre\u2013Leiden\n |date        = 13 April 2011\n |title       = Queen's Day\n |accessdate  = 1 May 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120323114508/http://www.expatcentreleiden.nl/news/news_item/t/queen_s_day\n |archivedate = 23 March 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n''Koninginnedag'' celebrations have sometimes been affected or disrupted. In 1988 three British servicemen stationed in Germany who were in the Netherlands for ''Koninginnedag'' were killed in [[Irish Republican Army]] attacks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Raines|first=Howell\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/02/world/3-british-servicemen-are-killed-in-ira-attacks-in-netherlands.html\n  | periodical = [[The New York Times]]\n  | date = 2 May 1988\n  | title =3 British servicemen are killed in I.R.A. attacks in Netherlands\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011}}</ref> In 1996 the celebrations in [[Rotterdam]] were dampened by an alcohol ban, put in place following riots earlier in the week after local football club [[Feyenoord]] won the [[Eredivisie|Dutch league championship]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Corder|first=Mike\n  | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8NMoAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ws8EAAAAIBAJ&dq=queen's%20day%20netherlands&pg=4809%2C35231\n  | periodical = AP via Lewiston Herald-Journal\n  | date = 1 May 1996\n  | title =Netherlands celebrates Queen Mother's birthday with national garage sale\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011}}</ref> The Queen's scheduled 2001 visits to [[Hoogeveen]] and [[Meppel]] were postponed for one year owing to an outbreak of [[foot-and-mouth disease]].<ref name=\"placelist\" />\n\nOn 30 April 2009, Beatrix and other members of the royal family were at the town of [[Apeldoorn]] when a 38-year-old man, Karst Tates, [[2009 attack on the Dutch royal family|drove his Suzuki Swift automobile into the crowd]], narrowly missing the open-top bus the royal family members were riding on.<ref name=\"mag\" /><ref name=\"BBCreport\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/8026807.stm | title = Car crash into Dutch Queen parade | publisher = BBC | date = 30 April 2009|accessdate = 1 May 2011 }}</ref> Seven people were killed and further celebrations were cancelled.<ref name=\"BBCreport\" /> Tates died of injuries sustained in the attack soon afterwards and his exact motives remain unclear, though it appears his target was the royal family.<ref name=\"mag\" /> The incident provoked questions about whether the royal family should continue to participate in the celebrations. However, Beatrix indicated that the tragedy would not stop her from meeting her people.<ref name=\"nick\" /> In 2010, Beatrix and her family visited [[Wemeldinge]] and [[Middelburg]], in [[Zeeland]] province. There were no incidents, and afterwards, the Queen thanked Zeeland for giving ''Koninginnedag'' back to her family, and to her country.<ref name=\"mag\"/>\n\n[[File:Beatrixwoudrichem2007.jpg|thumb|upright|Queen Beatrix and her son and heir [[Willem-Alexander, Prince of Orange]] (waving) visit [[Woudrichem]] in 2007]]\nQueen Beatrix visited the following towns and cities over the years on ''Koninginnedag'':<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/inhoud/geschiedenis-koningsdag |title=Geschiedenis Koningsdag |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n{{columns|width=50%\n|col1 = \n*1981: [[Veere]] and [[Breda]]\n*1982: [[Harlingen, Netherlands|Harlingen]] and [[Zuidlaren]]\n*1983: [[Lochem]] and [[Vaassen]]\n*1984: [[The Hague]]\n*1985: [[Anna Paulowna]], [[Callantsoog]], and [[Schagen]]\n*1986: [[Deurne, Netherlands|Deurne]] and [[Meijel]]\n*1987: [[Breukelen]]\n*1988: [[Genemuiden]], [[Kampen (Overijssel)|Kampen]], and informally [[Amsterdam]]\n*1989: [[Goedereede]] and [[Oud-Beijerland]]\n*1990: [[Haren (Groningen)|Haren]] and [[Loppersum]]\n*1991: [[Buren]] and [[Culemborg]]\n*1992: [[Rotterdam]]\n*1993: [[Vlieland]] and [[Sneek]]\n*1994: [[Emmeloord]] and [[Urk]]\n*1995: [[Eijsden]] and [[Sittard]]\n*1996: [[Sint Maartensdijk]] and [[Bergen op Zoom]]\n|col2 = \n*1997: [[Marken]] and [[Velsen]]\n*1998: [[Doesburg]] and [[Zutphen]]\n*1999: [[Houten]] and [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]]\n*2000: [[Katwijk]] and [[Leiden]]\n*2001: ''visits cancelled''\n*2002: [[Hoogeveen]] and [[Meppel]]\n*2003: [[Wijhe]] and [[Deventer]]\n*2004: [[Warffum]] and [[Groningen (city)|Groningen]]\n*2005: [[Scheveningen]] and [[The Hague]]\n*2006: [[Zeewolde]] and [[Almere]]\n*2007: [[Woudrichem]] and [['s-Hertogenbosch]]\n*2008: [[W\u00fbnseradiel|Makkum]] and [[Franeker]]\n*2009: [[Apeldoorn]] ([[2009 attack on the Dutch royal family]])\n*2010: [[Wemeldinge]] and [[Middelburg]]<ref name=\"placelist\">{{cite web\n |title=Koninginnedag \n |url=http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/encyclopedie/monarchie/koninginnedag/ \n |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] \n |accessdate=30 April 2012 \n |language=nl \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607051723/http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/encyclopedie/monarchie/koninginnedag \n |archive-date= 7 June 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n*2011: [[Weert]] and [[Thorn (Netherlands)|Thorn]]<ref name=\"dutchnews\">{{cite web\n  | title =The Netherlands celebrates Queen's Day, royals in Limburg\n  | url = http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2011/04/the_netherlands_celebrates_que.php\n  | publisher = dutchnews.nl\n  | date = 30 April 2011\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>\n*2012: [[Rhenen]] and [[Veenendaal]]\n*2013: ''visits cancelled''<ref name=\"2013-cancelled\">{{cite web\n  | title=Amstelveen 'beetje teleurgesteld'\n  | url=https://nos.nl/artikel/467481-amstelveen-beetje-teleurgesteld.html\n  | publisher=NOS\n  | date=28 January 2013\n  | accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nOn 28 January 2013 Queen Beatrix announced her abdication on 30 April 2013 in favour of her son, [[Willem-Alexander, Prince of Orange|Willem-Alexander]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/28/queen-beatrix-netherlands-abdicates |newspaper=Guardian |date=28 January 2012 |title=Dutch Queen announces Abdication |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> Since this date coincided with ''Koninginnedag'' the royal family's planned visit to [[De Rijp]] and [[Amstelveen]] was cancelled,<ref name=\"2013-cancelled\" /> although ''Koninginnedag'' 2013 was still celebrated throughout the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nederland viert laatste Koninginnedag |url=https://nos.nl/video/501664-nederland-viert-laatste-koninginnedag.html |publisher=NOS |date=30 April 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=700.000 mensen bezochten A'dam |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/501899-700-000-mensen-bezochten-a-dam.html |publisher=NOS |date=30 April 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Topdrukte in Brabantse steden, Koninginnedag verloopt rustig \u2013 Foto's |url=http://www.omroepbrabant.nl/?news/192841832/Topdrukte+in+Brabantse+steden,+Koninginnedag+verloopt+rustig+-+Fotos.aspx |publisher=Omroep Brabant |date=30 April 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Willem-Alexander===\n[[File:Koningsdag Graft-De Rijp 20140426.jpg|thumb|King Willem-Alexander, Queen Maxima and Princess Beatrix during the celebration of ''Koningsdag'' 2014 in [[De Rijp]]]]\n[[File:Waterland, Amsterdam, Netherlands - panoramio (13).jpg|thumb|[[Waterland]]'s ''Koningsdag'' bike race (2015)]]\nOn 30 April 2013, Queen's Day, [[Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands|Willem-Alexander]] succeeded his mother [[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Beatrix]] and became the first King of the Netherlands in 123 years. Consequently, from 2014 onwards the name has been changed from Queen's Day to King's Day. The date has also changed from 30 to 27 April, which is the birthday of Willem-Alexander.<ref name=\"BWBR0032908\"/> On the first King's Day \u2013 held on 26 April 2014 because 27 April 2014 was a Sunday \u2013 the king visited [[De Rijp]] and [[Amstelveen]] (originally planned to be visited by Queen Beatrix in 2013, but postponed due to her abdication).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2013/01/28/koninginnedag-wordt-koiningsdag-en-is-voortaan-op-27-april/ |author=Anouk Eigenraam |title=Koninginnedag wordt Koningsdag en is voortaan op 27 april |language=Dutch |newspaper=NRC Handelsblad |date=28 January 2013 |access-date=29 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nKing Willem-Alexander visited the following towns and cities over the years on ''Koningsdag'':\n{{columns|width=50%\n|col1 = \n*2014: [[De Rijp]] and [[Amstelveen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2013/01/28/koningsdag-vanaf-2014-op-27-april |title=Koningsdag vanaf 2014 op 27 april |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=28 January 2013 |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*2015: [[Dordrecht]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2014/10/11/koningsdag-2015-in-dordrecht |title=Koningsdag 2015 in Dordrecht |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=11 October 2014 |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*2016: [[Zwolle]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2015/10/12/koningsdag-2016-in-zwolle |title=Koningsdag 2016 in Zwolle |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=12 October 2015 |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*2017: [[Tilburg]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2016/09/02/koningsdag-2017-in-tilburg |title=Koningsdag 2017 in Tilburg |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=2 September 2016 |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*2018: [[Groningen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2017/09/14/koningsdag-2018-in-groningen |title=Koningsdag 2018 in Groningen |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=14 September 2017 |access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n*2019: [[Amersfoort]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2018/08/30/koningsdag-2019-in-amersfoort |title=Koningsdag 2019 in Amersfoort |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=30 August 2018 |access-date=27 April 2019}}</ref>\n*2020: ''visit cancelled'' \n}}Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], many King's day celebrations were cancelled in 2020, including the royal family's planned visit to [[Maastricht]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://koningsdag2020.bezoekmaastricht.nl/pers/persberichten/koningsdag-maastricht-2020-gaat-niet-door|title=Koningsdag Maastricht 2020 gaat niet door|website=Bezoek Maastricht|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2327286|title=Koningsdag in Maastricht en koningsspelen afgelast wegens coronavirus|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> An alternative stay-at-home program was issued instead, featuring a simultaneous [[Wilhelmus|national anthem]] sing-along and a national [[Toast (honor)|toast]] moment. The King addressed the Dutch people from his home.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2331791|title=Koningsdag 2020: 'Misschien een beetje rommelig, maar dat hoort erbij'|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe festivities on ''Koningsdag'' are often organised by Orange Committees (Dutch: ''Oranjecomit\u00e9''), local associations<ref name=\"nu\" /> that seek sponsorship and donations for their activities. In recent years some committees have had difficulty in recruiting new members from among the younger Dutch.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Woerden: Oranjecomit\u00e9 zoekt sponsors\n  | url =http://www.rplfm.nl/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=123&Itemid=72?limit_start=0&pid=10952\n  | publisher = RPLFM Woerden\n  | date = 29 April 2011\n  | accessdate = 5 May 2011|language=nl}}.</ref>\n\n===Flea market===\n[[File:Koninginnedag 2011 Deventer.jpg|thumb|''Vrijmarkt'', ''Koninginnedag'' 2011, [[Deventer]]]]\nThe ''vrijmarkt'' (literally 'free market') is a nationwide [[flea market]], at which many people sell their [[used good]]s. ''Koningsdag'' is the one day of the year that the Dutch government permits sales on the street without a permit and without the payment of [[value added tax]].<ref name=\"tnt\">{{cite journal|last=Chack|first=Erin\n  | title = Queen's Day Amsterdam 2011 guide\n  | periodical = TNT Magazine\n  | date = 5 April 2011\n  | url = http://www.tntmagazine.com/tnt-today/archive/2011/04/05/Queen_2700_s-Day-Amsterdam-2011-guide.aspx\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> [[ING Group|ING Bank]] found in 2011 that one in five Dutch residents planned to sell at the ''vrijmarkt'' and estimated they would earn \u20ac100 per person for a total turnover of \u20ac290&nbsp;million. Over half of the Dutch people buy at the ''vrijmarkt''; ING Bank predicted they would spend \u20ac28 each at the 2011 ''vrijmarkt''.<ref name=\"ing\">{{cite web\n  | title = Nederlanders rekenen op 290 miljoen op vrijmarkt\n  | publisher = ING Group\n  | date = 29 April 2011\n  | url = http://www.ing.nl/nieuws/nieuws_en_persberichten/2011/04/nederlanders_rekenen_op_290_miljoen_op_vrijmarkt.aspx\n  | accessdate = 30 April 2012|language=nl}}</ref> Queen Beatrix has been known to buy at the ''vrijmarkt''; in 1995 she purchased a floor lamp.<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = National yard sale honors Dutch queen\n  | periodical = AP via The Southeast Missourian\n  | date = 1 May 1997\n  | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5VApAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M9gEAAAAIBAJ&dq=queen's%20day%20netherlands&pg=6104%2C9806310\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011}}</ref> The bank also forecast that the lowest level of sales at the ''vrijmarkt'' in 2011 would be in the province of [[Limburg (Netherlands)|Limburg]], site of Queen Beatrix's visit.<ref name=\"ing\" />\n\nAmong the most popular areas for the ''vrijmarkt'' in Amsterdam is the [[Jordaan]] quarter, but the wide Apollolaan in front of the Hilton hotel in southern Amsterdam is gaining in popularity. Children sell their cast-off toys or garments at the [[Vondelpark]], also in southern Amsterdam, and in a spirit of fun passers-by often offer the young sellers more than they are asking for the goods.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.amsterdam.info/queensday/market/\n  | publisher = amsterdam.info\n  | title =Free market on Queen's Day\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> Until 1996, the ''vrijmarkt'' began the evening before and continued for 24&nbsp;hours. This was ended in the hope of gaining a pause in the celebrations so preparations could be made for the daytime activities.<ref name=\"mag\" /> [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]], uniquely among Dutch municipalities, retains the overnight ''vrijmarkt''.<ref name=\"dutchnews\" /> In 2020, people can sell their goods on an online platform to avoid physical contact with customers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Festivities===\n''Koningsdag'' now sees large-scale celebrations, with many concerts and special events in public spaces, particularly in Amsterdam. An outdoor concert is held on Amsterdam's [[Museumplein]], where as many as 800,000&nbsp;people may gather. To aid visitors in returning home by train after the festivities outdoor events must end by 20:00, and the Museumplein show by 21:00.<ref name=\"dutchnews\" /> The city centre is closed to cars, and no trams ride in the heart of the city; people are urged to avoid [[Amsterdam Centraal railway station]] and use other stations if possible from their direction. International trains that normally begin or terminate at Amsterdam Centraal are instead directed to a suburban stop.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.amsterdam.info/queensday/transportation/\n  | publisher = amsterdam.info\n  | title =Transportation during the Queen's Day\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Leaf - Koninginnenach 2008.jpg|thumb|A concert given by the Dutch band [[Leaf (Dutch band)|Leaf]] in [[The Hague]] during ''Koninginnenacht'' in 2008]]\n[[File:DirkvdM koninginnedag 3.jpg|thumb|Revellers dressed in orange in Amsterdam, ''Koninginnedag'' 2007]]\n\nIn recent years parties and concerts have been held the evening before ''Koningsdag''. Until 2013, nightclubs across the Netherlands organised special events for what became known as ''Koninginnenacht'' (Queen's Night).<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.amsterdam.info/queensday\n  | publisher = amsterdam.info\n  | title = Queen's Day in Amsterdam\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> Many young people celebrate in the streets and squares (and in Amsterdam, the canals as well) throughout the night, and after all-night partying join the crowds at the ''vrijmarkt''.<ref name=\"nick\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Thompson\n  | first = Nick\n  | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/04/22/netherlands.queens.day/?hpt=C2 | publisher = [[CNN]]\n  | date = 25 April 2011\n  | title = Queen's Day: Go Dutch for an alternative royal celebration\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>\n{{Anchor|2009 Apeldoorn car accident}}\n\nWhile King's Day celebrations take place throughout the Netherlands, Amsterdam is a popular destination for many revellers. Often the city's 850,000 residents are joined by up to 1 million visitors. In recent years Amsterdam authorities have taken some measures to try to stem the flow of visitors as the city became too crowded.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.dutchamsterdam.nl/2310-amsterdam-says-new-approach-to-queens-day-successful\n  | publisher = dutchamsterdam.nl\n  | title = Amsterdam says new approach to Queen's Day successful\n  | accessdate = 26 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThose taking part in ''Koningsdag'' commonly dye their hair orange or wear orange clothing in honour of the [[House of Orange-Nassau]], which rules over the Netherlands. Orange-coloured drinks are also popular.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.amsterdam.info/queensday/tradition/\n  | publisher = amsterdam.info\n  | title =Tradition of Queen's Day in Holland\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> This colour choice is sometimes dubbed \"orange madness\", or in Dutch, ''[[oranjegekte]]''.<ref name=\"nick\" /> A local Orange Committee member said of ''Koninginnedag'' in 2011:\n\n<blockquote>Friendships\u2014and community\u2014will be formed. For me that's really what Queen's Day is all about. It's not an outburst of patriotism, it's not even about the popularity of the royal family. It's about a sense of belonging. For one day, everybody is the same in Holland. Bright orange and barmy.<ref name=\"plan\" /></blockquote>\n\nChildren celebrate with a variety of games including ''koekhappen'' (in which they catch spice cake dangling from a string in their mouths) and ''spijker poepen'' (in which they tie string around their waist a nail dangling at one end, which they attempt to lower into a glass bottle).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/04/22/netherlands.queens.day/|title=Queen's Day: Go Dutch for an alternative royal celebration - CNN.com|last=Thompson|first=Nick|date=25 April 2011|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Honours===\n''Koningsdag'' is an opportunity for the monarch to honour citizens for their service to the Netherlands. In 2011, Queen Beatrix issued an honours list noting the work of 3,357&nbsp;people, most of whom became members of the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]].<ref>{{Cite news\n  | url = http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/dutch-queen\u2019s-day-honours-list\n  | publisher =Radio Netherlands Worldwide\n  | date = 29 April 2011\n  | title =Dutch Queen's Day honours list\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Observance in Dutch territories outside Europe==\n''Koningsdag'' is also celebrated in [[Aruba]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]], and [[Sint Maarten]], constituent countries of the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]].<ref name=\"nick\" /> It is less widely celebrated on the Caribbean island of [[Bonaire]], also a part of the Kingdom, where the local celebration of Dia di Rincon (held on 30 April) is more popular.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title = Dia di Rincon populairder dan Koninginnedag op Bonaire\n  | publisher = Radio Netherlands Worldwide (Caribbean)\n  | date = 2 May 2011\n  | url = http://www.rnw.nl/caribiana/article/dia-di-rincon-populairder-dan-koninginnedag-op-bonaire\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011|language=nl}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Koningsdag}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Koninginnedag}}\n\n{{Public holidays in the Netherlands}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:Dutch monarchy]]\n[[Category:Dutch society]]\n[[Category:Dutch words and phrases]]\n[[Category:National days]]\n[[Category:National holidays]]\n[[Category:Birthdays of heads of state]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Annual events in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Spring (season) events in the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Queen's Day}}\n{{for|the Belgian Kings day|King's Feast}}\n{{short description|Dutch national holiday}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name = ''Koningsdag''\n|type         = national\n|longtype     = [[Public holiday|National holiday]]\n|image        = Amsterdam's Canals.jpg\n|caption      = People dressed in orange on the [[canals of Amsterdam]] in 2010\n|observedby   = [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] ([[Netherlands]], [[Aruba]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Sint&nbsp;Maarten]])\n|date         = 27 April (26 April if 27 April is a Sunday)\n|celebrations = Partying, [[Oranjegekte|wearing orange]] costumes, [[flea market]]s, concerts and traditional local gatherings\n|significance = Birthday of [[King Willem-Alexander]]\n|duration     = 1 day\n|frequency    = annual\n}}\n\n'''''Koningsdag''''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8ko\u02d0n\u026a\u014bzd\u0251x|-|Nl-Koningsdag.ogg}}) or '''King's Day''' is a [[public holiday|national holiday]] in the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]]. Celebrated on 27 April (26 April if the 27th is a Sunday), the date marks the birth of [[King Willem-Alexander]].<ref name=\"BWBR0032908\">{{cite journal|url=http://wetten.overheid.nl/BWBR0032908/geldigheidsdatum_01-01-2014|title=Besluit vaststelling en aanduiding zevenentwintigste april als Koningsdag|id=BWBR0032908|language=nl|date=30 April 2013|authorlink=Ministry of General Affairs|author=AZ}}</ref> Until the [[abdication]] of [[Queen Beatrix]] in 2013, the holiday was known as '''''Koninginnedag''''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02ccko\u02d0n\u026a\u014b\u02c8\u026an\u0259d\u0251x|-|Nl-koninginnedag.ogg}}) or '''Queen's Day''' and was celebrated on 30 April.\n\nThe holiday was initially observed on 31 August 1885 as ''Prinsessedag'' or Princess's Day, the fifth birthday of [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Princess Wilhelmina]], then [[heir presumptive]] to the Dutch throne. On her accession in November 1890 the holiday acquired the name ''Koninginnedag'', first celebrated on 31 August 1891. In September 1948, Wilhelmina's daughter [[Juliana of the Netherlands|Juliana]] ascended to the throne and the holiday was moved to her birthday, 30 April. The holiday was celebrated on this date from 1949.\n\nJuliana's daughter, Beatrix, retained the celebration on 30 April after she ascended the throne in 1980, though her birthday was on 31 January.<ref name=\"BWBR0031338\">{{cite journal|url=http://wetten.overheid.nl/BWBR0031338/geldigheidsdatum_01-05-2002|title=Besluit aanduiding van de dertigste april als Koninginnedag|id=BWBR0031338|language=nl|date=24 April 1980|authorlink=Ministry of General Affairs|author=AZ}}</ref> Beatrix altered her mother's custom of receiving a floral parade at [[Soestdijk Palace]], instead choosing to visit different Dutch towns each year and join in the festivities with her children.\n\nIn 2009, the Queen was celebrating Queen's Day in the city of [[Apeldoorn]] when [[2009 attack on the Dutch royal family|a man attempted to attack her]] by trying to ram the royal family's bus with his car; instead he drove into a crowd of people and crashed into a monument: seven people in the crowd were killed, as was the driver.\n\nQueen Beatrix abdicated on ''Koninginnedag'' 2013, and her son, Willem-Alexander, ascended the throne (the first king since the observance of the national holiday). As a result, the holiday became known as ''Koningsdag'' from 2014 on, and the celebration was shifted three days backwards to 27 April, the King's birthday.\n\n''Koningsdag'' is known for its nationwide ''vrijmarkt'' (\"free market\"), at which the Dutch sell their used items. It is also an opportunity for \"orange madness\" or ''[[oranjegekte]]'', a kind of frenzy named for the national colour.\n\n==History==\n===Wilhelmina (1885\u20131948)===\n[[File:Oranjefeestvreugde in Amsterdam.ogv|thumb|thumbtime=3|right|''Koninginnedag'' on 31 August 1932 in Amsterdam]]\n\nFaced with an unpopular monarchy, in the 1880s the [[Liberal Union (Netherlands)|liberals]] in Dutch government sought a means of promoting national unity.<ref name=\"nu\" /> King [[William III of the Netherlands|William III]] was disliked, but his four-year-old daughter [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Princess Wilhelmina]] was not.<ref name=\"mag\" /> A holiday honouring King William had been intermittently held on his birthday, and J. W. R. Gerlach, editor of the newspaper ''Utrechts Provinciaal en Stedelijk Dagblad'', proposed that the princess's birthday be observed as an opportunity for patriotic celebration and national reconciliation.<ref name=\"dag\">{{Cite book\n  | last =Deploige\n  | first = Jeroen\n  |author2=Gita Deneckere\n   | title = Mystifying the Monarch: Studies on Discourse, Power, and History\n  | publisher = Amsterdam University Press\n  | location = Amsterdam\n  | year =2006\n  | page = 187\n  | isbn = 90-5356-767-4\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=OLHNKiSKvBwC&dq=Prinsessedag&source=gbs_navlinks_s\n  | accessdate = 6 May 2011 }}</ref> ''Prinsessedag'' or Princess's Day was first celebrated in the Netherlands on 31 August 1885, Wilhelmina's fifth birthday. The young princess was paraded through the streets, waving to the crowds.<ref name=\"mag\" /> The first observance occurred only in [[Utrecht]], but other municipalities quickly began to observe it, organizing activities for children.<ref name=\"dag\" /> Further processions were held in the following years, and when Wilhelmina inherited the throne in 1890, ''Prinsessedag'' was renamed ''Koninginnedag'', or Queen's Day.<ref name=\"mag\" /> By then almost every Dutch town and city was marking the holiday.<ref name=\"dag\" />\n\nThe celebration proved popular, and when the Queen came of age in 1898, her inauguration was postponed a week to 6 September so as not to interfere with ''Koninginnedag''.<ref name=\"plan\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Chadwick\n  | first = Nicola\n  | title = Planning the perfect Queen's Day\n  | publisher = Radio Netherlands Worldwide\n  | date = 27 April 2011\n  | url = http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/planning-perfect-queens-day\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110430040355/http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/planning-perfect-queens-day\n  | archive-date = 30 April 2011\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref> The annual holiday fell on the final day of school [[summer vacation]], which made it popular among schoolchildren.<ref name=\"mag\">{{Cite journal\n |last        = Peek\n |first       = Mike\n |title       = Long live the Queen\n |journal     = Amsterdam Magazine\n |pages       = 29\u201333\n |date        = April 2011\n |url         = http://amsterdam-magazine.com/2011/04/feature-long-life-the-queen/\n |accessdate  = 30 April 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110811112446/http://amsterdam-magazine.com/2011/04/feature-long-life-the-queen/\n |archivedate = 11 August 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> It is uncertain how much Wilhelmina enjoyed the festivities; although writer Mike Peek, in a 2011 magazine article about ''Koninginnedag'', suggests she was enthusiastic,<ref name=\"mag\" /> there is a story of Wilhelmina, after a tired return from one of these birthday processions, making her doll bow until the toy's hair was dishevelled, and telling it, \"Now you shall sit in a carriage and bow until your back aches, and see how much you like being a Queen!\"<ref>{{Cite journal\n  | last = Bates\n  | first = Winslow\n  | title = The girl queen and her coronation\n  | journal = National Magazine\n  | pages = 12\u201318\n  | date = October 1898\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oYzNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA17\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n''Koninginnedag'' 1902 not only honoured the Queen's birthday, but was celebrated with increased enthusiasm as it marked her recovery from serious illness.<ref name=\"nu\">{{cite web\n |title=The Queen's official birthday (Koninginnedag) \n |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] \n |url=http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/globale-paginas/taalrubrieken/english/monarchy/the-queens-official-birthday-(koninginnedag)/ \n |accessdate=30 April 2012 \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506033422/http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/globale-paginas/taalrubrieken/english/monarchy/the-queens-official-birthday-%28koninginnedag%29 \n |archive-date= 6 May 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> Wilhelmina rarely attended ''Koninginnedag'' festivities after reaching adulthood.<ref name=\"old\" /> She attended ceremonies for her silver jubilee in 1923, which included massive festivities in Amsterdam and [[The Hague]], despite the Queen's request that large sums not be spent because economic conditions at the time were difficult. To ensure that even the poorer parts of the city were included, bands played simultaneously at 28&nbsp;locations across The Hague.<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news\n  | title = Holland preparing for Queen's jubilee\n  | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10A16F9345416738DDDA00894DF405B838EF1D3\n  | newspaper =[[The New York Times]]\n  | date = 9 July 1923\n  |page = 13\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Wilhelmina made further exceptions for such events as her fiftieth birthday in 1930.<ref name=\"old\">{{cite news\n |title       = Queen's Day history dates back to 1889\n |url         = http://www.nisnews.nl/dossiers/royal_house/260401_922.htm\n |publisher   = NIS News\n |date        = 26 April 2001\n |accessdate  = 1 May 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930192138/http://www.nisnews.nl/dossiers/royal_house/260401_922.htm\n |archivedate = 30 September 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> During the [[German occupation of the Netherlands]] during World War II, ''Koninginnedag'' celebrations were banned, and members of the Orange Committees, which organize the holiday events, destroyed their records for fear of German reprisals.<ref name=\"plan\" />\n\n===Juliana (1948\u20131980)===\n[[File:Arnhem Parade 30 april B.jpg|thumb|thumbtime=3|thumb|right|Military parade in [[Arnhem]], ''Koninginnedag'' 1958]]\nAnother summertime birthday celebration in the Netherlands was that of Wilhelmina's mother, [[Emma of the Netherlands|Queen-Regent Emma]], who after Wilhelmina attained adulthood generally spent her own birthday, 2 August, at [[Soestdijk Palace]] in [[Baarn]]. Until her death in 1934, Emma received [[Bloemencorso|an annual floral tribute]] from the townsfolk on her birthday. In 1937 Wilhelmina's daughter and heiress, [[Juliana of the Netherlands|Princess Juliana]], took up residence at Soestdijk Palace following her marriage, and the townsfolk made their floral presentation to her, moving the date to Juliana's birthday, 30 April.<ref name=\"old\" /> In September 1948 Juliana ascended to the Dutch throne and from 1949 onwards ''Koninginnedag'' was on her birthday.<ref name=\"man\">{{cite news\n  | title = Queen's Day of Netherlands April 30, 2011\n  | url = http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/316226/queens-day-netherlands-april-30-2011\n  | periodical = Manila Bulletin\n  | date = 30 April 2011\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> The change in date attracted immediate approval from Dutch children, who gained an extra day of holiday. The first observance of the holiday on the new date included a huge circus at the [[Olympic Stadium (Amsterdam)|Amsterdam Olympic Stadium]]\u2014one not attended by the royal family, who remained at Soestdijk Palace.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schorr|first=Danel L.\n  | title = Dutch queen guides nations through crises, eyes first anniversary\n  | url = https://secure.pqarchiver.com/csmonitor_historic/access/171767732.html?FMT=AI&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+16%2C+1949&author=By+Daniel+L.+Schorr+Special+Correspondent+of+The+Christian+Science+Monitor&pub=Christian+Science+Monitor&desc=Dutch+Queen+Guides+Nation+Through+Crises%2C+Eyes+First+Anniversary\n  | periodical = [[The Christian Science Monitor]]\n  | date = 16 April 1949\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Queen Juliana retained the floral tribute, staying each year on ''Koninginnedag'' at Soestdijk Palace to receive it. The parade became televised in the 1950s, and ''Koninginnedag'' increasingly became a national holiday, with workers given the day off.<ref name=\"nu\" /> Juliana had a reputation as a \"queen of the people\", and according to Peek, \"it felt as if she invited her subjects to the royal home\".<ref name=\"mag\" />\n\nIn early 1966 Juliana's eldest daughter, Princess Beatrix, married [[Prince Claus of the Netherlands|Klaus-Georg von Amsberg]]. The marriage was controversial because the new Prince Claus (as he was dubbed) was a German, and Claus himself had served in the [[Wehrmacht|German Army]] during the war.  Anti-German riots in Amsterdam marred the wedding day and the following observances of ''Koninginnedag''. Fearing further demonstrations on the holiday, government officials decided to open Amsterdam city centre to the ''vrijmarkt'' (\"free market\") that had long been held on ''Koninginnedag'' in the outskirts of town, principally for children. The ''vrijmarkt'' occupied the space where demonstrations might have been held, and began a new custom.<ref name=\"mag\" />\n\n===Beatrix (1980\u20132013)===\n[[File:Beatrixscheveningen2005.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Queen Beatrix]] speaks with the mayor of [[The Hague]], [[Wim Deetman]] in [[Scheveningen]], ''Koninginnedag'' 2005.]]\nWhen [[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Queen Beatrix]] succeeded her mother Juliana on the latter's abdication on 30 April 1980, the new queen decided to keep the holiday on 30 April as a tribute to her mother.<ref name=\"BWBR0031338\"/><ref name=\"nu\"/> (If 30 April fell on a Sunday, ''Koninginnedag'' was observed the previous day\u2014this occurred most recently in 2006.<ref name=\"joel\">{{Cite news\n  | last = Romanko\n  | first = J.R.\n  | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE7D91031F93AA25750C0A9609C8B63&scp=8&sq=queen's%20Day%20Netherlands&st=cse\n  | periodical = [[The New York Times]]\n  | date = 19 March 2006\n  | title =Datebook\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>) The reason was practical as well\u2014Beatrix's actual birthday on 31 January would have been less conducive to the traditional outdoor activities.<ref name=\"man\" /> Rather than remaining at the palace and letting the Dutch people come to her, Beatrix instead usually visited two towns each year for ''Koninginnedag'' celebrations.<ref name=\"nu\" /> Local crafts and customs were demonstrated for the royal family, who had the opportunity to join in.<ref name=\"nick\" /><ref>{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.expatcentreleiden.nl/news/news_item/t/queen_s_day\n |publisher   = Expat Centre\u2013Leiden\n |date        = 13 April 2011\n |title       = Queen's Day\n |accessdate  = 1 May 2011\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120323114508/http://www.expatcentreleiden.nl/news/news_item/t/queen_s_day\n |archivedate = 23 March 2012\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n''Koninginnedag'' celebrations have sometimes been affected or disrupted. In 1988 three British servicemen stationed in Germany who were in the Netherlands for ''Koninginnedag'' were killed in [[Irish Republican Army]] attacks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Raines|first=Howell\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/02/world/3-british-servicemen-are-killed-in-ira-attacks-in-netherlands.html\n  | periodical = [[The New York Times]]\n  | date = 2 May 1988\n  | title =3 British servicemen are killed in I.R.A. attacks in Netherlands\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011}}</ref> In 1996 the celebrations in [[Rotterdam]] were dampened by an alcohol ban, put in place following riots earlier in the week after local football club [[Feyenoord]] won the [[Eredivisie|Dutch league championship]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Corder|first=Mike\n  | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8NMoAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ws8EAAAAIBAJ&dq=queen's%20day%20netherlands&pg=4809%2C35231\n  | periodical = AP via Lewiston Herald-Journal\n  | date = 1 May 1996\n  | title =Netherlands celebrates Queen Mother's birthday with national garage sale\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011}}</ref> The Queen's scheduled 2001 visits to [[Hoogeveen]] and [[Meppel]] were postponed for one year owing to an outbreak of [[foot-and-mouth disease]].<ref name=\"placelist\" />\n\nOn 30 April 2009, Beatrix and other members of the royal family were at the town of [[Apeldoorn]] when a 38-year-old man, Karst Tates, [[2009 attack on the Dutch royal family|drove his Suzuki Swift automobile into the crowd]], narrowly missing the open-top bus the royal family members were riding on.<ref name=\"mag\" /><ref name=\"BBCreport\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/8026807.stm | title = Car crash into Dutch Queen parade | publisher = BBC | date = 30 April 2009|accessdate = 1 May 2011 }}</ref> Seven people were killed and further celebrations were cancelled.<ref name=\"BBCreport\" /> Tates died of injuries sustained in the attack soon afterwards and his exact motives remain unclear, though it appears his target was the royal family.<ref name=\"mag\" /> The incident provoked questions about whether the royal family should continue to participate in the celebrations. However, Beatrix indicated that the tragedy would not stop her from meeting her people.<ref name=\"nick\" /> In 2010, Beatrix and her family visited [[Wemeldinge]] and [[Middelburg]], in [[Zeeland]] province. There were no incidents, and afterwards, the Queen thanked Zeeland for giving ''Koninginnedag'' back to her family, and to her country.<ref name=\"mag\"/>\n\n[[File:Beatrixwoudrichem2007.jpg|thumb|upright|Queen Beatrix and her son and heir [[Willem-Alexander, Prince of Orange]] (waving) visit [[Woudrichem]] in 2007]]\nQueen Beatrix visited the following towns and cities over the years on ''Koninginnedag'':<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/inhoud/geschiedenis-koningsdag |title=Geschiedenis Koningsdag |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n{{columns|width=50%\n|col1 = \n*1981: [[Veere]] and [[Breda]]\n*1982: [[Harlingen, Netherlands|Harlingen]] and [[Zuidlaren]]\n*1983: [[Lochem]] and [[Vaassen]]\n*1984: [[The Hague]]\n*1985: [[Anna Paulowna]], [[Callantsoog]], and [[Schagen]]\n*1986: [[Deurne, Netherlands|Deurne]] and [[Meijel]]\n*1987: [[Breukelen]]\n*1988: [[Genemuiden]], [[Kampen (Overijssel)|Kampen]], and informally [[Amsterdam]]\n*1989: [[Goedereede]] and [[Oud-Beijerland]]\n*1990: [[Haren (Groningen)|Haren]] and [[Loppersum]]\n*1991: [[Buren]] and [[Culemborg]]\n*1992: [[Rotterdam]]\n*1993: [[Vlieland]] and [[Sneek]]\n*1994: [[Emmeloord]] and [[Urk]]\n*1995: [[Eijsden]] and [[Sittard]]\n*1996: [[Sint Maartensdijk]] and [[Bergen op Zoom]]\n|col2 = \n*1997: [[Marken]] and [[Velsen]]\n*1998: [[Doesburg]] and [[Zutphen]]\n*1999: [[Houten]] and [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]]\n*2000: [[Katwijk]] and [[Leiden]]\n*2001: ''visits cancelled''\n*2002: [[Hoogeveen]] and [[Meppel]]\n*2003: [[Wijhe]] and [[Deventer]]\n*2004: [[Warffum]] and [[Groningen (city)|Groningen]]\n*2005: [[Scheveningen]] and [[The Hague]]\n*2006: [[Zeewolde]] and [[Almere]]\n*2007: [[Woudrichem]] and [['s-Hertogenbosch]]\n*2008: [[W\u00fbnseradiel|Makkum]] and [[Franeker]]\n*2009: [[Apeldoorn]] ([[2009 attack on the Dutch royal family]])\n*2010: [[Wemeldinge]] and [[Middelburg]]<ref name=\"placelist\">{{cite web\n |title=Koninginnedag \n |url=http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/encyclopedie/monarchie/koninginnedag/ \n |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] \n |accessdate=30 April 2012 \n |language=nl \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607051723/http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/encyclopedie/monarchie/koninginnedag \n |archive-date= 7 June 2012 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n*2011: [[Weert]] and [[Thorn (Netherlands)|Thorn]]<ref name=\"dutchnews\">{{cite web\n  | title =The Netherlands celebrates Queen's Day, royals in Limburg\n  | url = http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2011/04/the_netherlands_celebrates_que.php\n  | publisher = dutchnews.nl\n  | date = 30 April 2011\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>\n*2012: [[Rhenen]] and [[Veenendaal]]\n*2013: ''visits cancelled''<ref name=\"2013-cancelled\">{{cite web\n  | title=Amstelveen 'beetje teleurgesteld'\n  | url=https://nos.nl/artikel/467481-amstelveen-beetje-teleurgesteld.html\n  | publisher=NOS\n  | date=28 January 2013\n  | accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nOn 28 January 2013 Queen Beatrix announced her abdication on 30 April 2013 in favour of her son, [[Willem-Alexander, Prince of Orange|Willem-Alexander]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/28/queen-beatrix-netherlands-abdicates |newspaper=Guardian |date=28 January 2012 |title=Dutch Queen announces Abdication |accessdate=28 January 2013}}</ref> Since this date coincided with ''Koninginnedag'' the royal family's planned visit to [[De Rijp]] and [[Amstelveen]] was cancelled,<ref name=\"2013-cancelled\" /> although ''Koninginnedag'' 2013 was still celebrated throughout the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nederland viert laatste Koninginnedag |url=https://nos.nl/video/501664-nederland-viert-laatste-koninginnedag.html |publisher=NOS |date=30 April 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=700.000 mensen bezochten A'dam |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/501899-700-000-mensen-bezochten-a-dam.html |publisher=NOS |date=30 April 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Topdrukte in Brabantse steden, Koninginnedag verloopt rustig \u2013 Foto's |url=http://www.omroepbrabant.nl/?news/192841832/Topdrukte+in+Brabantse+steden,+Koninginnedag+verloopt+rustig+-+Fotos.aspx |publisher=Omroep Brabant |date=30 April 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Willem-Alexander===\n[[File:Koningsdag Graft-De Rijp 20140426.jpg|thumb|King Willem-Alexander, Queen Maxima and Princess Beatrix during the celebration of ''Koningsdag'' 2014 in [[De Rijp]]]]\n[[File:Waterland, Amsterdam, Netherlands - panoramio (13).jpg|thumb|[[Waterland]]'s ''Koningsdag'' bike race (2015)]]\nOn 30 April 2013, Queen's Day, [[Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands|Willem-Alexander]] succeeded his mother [[Beatrix of the Netherlands|Beatrix]] and became the first King of the Netherlands in 123 years. Consequently, from 2014 onwards the name has been changed from Queen's Day to King's Day. The date has also changed from 30 to 27 April, which is the birthday of Willem-Alexander.<ref name=\"BWBR0032908\"/> On the first King's Day \u2013 held on 26 April 2014 because 27 April 2014 was a Sunday \u2013 the king visited [[De Rijp]] and [[Amstelveen]] (originally planned to be visited by Queen Beatrix in 2013, but postponed due to her abdication).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2013/01/28/koninginnedag-wordt-koiningsdag-en-is-voortaan-op-27-april/ |author=Anouk Eigenraam |title=Koninginnedag wordt Koningsdag en is voortaan op 27 april |language=Dutch |newspaper=NRC Handelsblad |date=28 January 2013 |access-date=29 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nKing Willem-Alexander visited the following towns and cities over the years on ''Koningsdag'':\n{{columns|width=50%\n|col1 = \n*2014: [[De Rijp]] and [[Amstelveen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2013/01/28/koningsdag-vanaf-2014-op-27-april |title=Koningsdag vanaf 2014 op 27 april |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=28 January 2013 |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*2015: [[Dordrecht]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2014/10/11/koningsdag-2015-in-dordrecht |title=Koningsdag 2015 in Dordrecht |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=11 October 2014 |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*2016: [[Zwolle]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2015/10/12/koningsdag-2016-in-zwolle |title=Koningsdag 2016 in Zwolle |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=12 October 2015 |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*2017: [[Tilburg]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2016/09/02/koningsdag-2017-in-tilburg |title=Koningsdag 2017 in Tilburg |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=2 September 2016 |access-date=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*2018: [[Groningen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2017/09/14/koningsdag-2018-in-groningen |title=Koningsdag 2018 in Groningen |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=14 September 2017 |access-date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n*2019: [[Amersfoort]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/onderwerpen/koningsdag/nieuws/2018/08/30/koningsdag-2019-in-amersfoort |title=Koningsdag 2019 in Amersfoort |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Rijksvoorlichtingsdienst]] |date=30 August 2018 |access-date=27 April 2019}}</ref>\n*2020: ''visit cancelled'' \n}}Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], many King's day celebrations were cancelled in 2020, including the royal family's planned visit to [[Maastricht]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://koningsdag2020.bezoekmaastricht.nl/pers/persberichten/koningsdag-maastricht-2020-gaat-niet-door|title=Koningsdag Maastricht 2020 gaat niet door|website=Bezoek Maastricht|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2327286|title=Koningsdag in Maastricht en koningsspelen afgelast wegens coronavirus|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> An alternative stay-at-home program is issued instead, featuring a simultaneous [[Wilhelmus|national anthem]] sing-along and a national [[Toast (honor)|toast]] moment. The King will address the Dutch people from his home.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2331791|title=Koningsdag 2020: 'Misschien een beetje rommelig, maar dat hoort erbij'|website=nos.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-27}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe festivities on ''Koningsdag'' are often organised by Orange Committees (Dutch: ''Oranjecomit\u00e9''), local associations<ref name=\"nu\" /> that seek sponsorship and donations for their activities. In recent years some committees have had difficulty in recruiting new members from among the younger Dutch.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Woerden: Oranjecomit\u00e9 zoekt sponsors\n  | url =http://www.rplfm.nl/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=123&Itemid=72?limit_start=0&pid=10952\n  | publisher = RPLFM Woerden\n  | date = 29 April 2011\n  | accessdate = 5 May 2011|language=nl}}.</ref>\n\n===Flea market===\n[[File:Koninginnedag 2011 Deventer.jpg|thumb|''Vrijmarkt'', ''Koninginnedag'' 2011, [[Deventer]]]]\nThe ''vrijmarkt'' (literally 'free market') is a nationwide [[flea market]], at which many people sell their [[used good]]s. ''Koningsdag'' is the one day of the year that the Dutch government permits sales on the street without a permit and without the payment of [[value added tax]].<ref name=\"tnt\">{{cite journal|last=Chack|first=Erin\n  | title = Queen's Day Amsterdam 2011 guide\n  | periodical = TNT Magazine\n  | date = 5 April 2011\n  | url = http://www.tntmagazine.com/tnt-today/archive/2011/04/05/Queen_2700_s-Day-Amsterdam-2011-guide.aspx\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> [[ING Group|ING Bank]] found in 2011 that one in five Dutch residents planned to sell at the ''vrijmarkt'' and estimated they would earn \u20ac100 per person for a total turnover of \u20ac290&nbsp;million. Over half of the Dutch people buy at the ''vrijmarkt''; ING Bank predicted they would spend \u20ac28 each at the 2011 ''vrijmarkt''.<ref name=\"ing\">{{cite web\n  | title = Nederlanders rekenen op 290 miljoen op vrijmarkt\n  | publisher = ING Group\n  | date = 29 April 2011\n  | url = http://www.ing.nl/nieuws/nieuws_en_persberichten/2011/04/nederlanders_rekenen_op_290_miljoen_op_vrijmarkt.aspx\n  | accessdate = 30 April 2012|language=nl}}</ref> Queen Beatrix has been known to buy at the ''vrijmarkt''; in 1995 she purchased a floor lamp.<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = National yard sale honors Dutch queen\n  | periodical = AP via The Southeast Missourian\n  | date = 1 May 1997\n  | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5VApAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M9gEAAAAIBAJ&dq=queen's%20day%20netherlands&pg=6104%2C9806310\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011}}</ref> The bank also forecast that the lowest level of sales at the ''vrijmarkt'' in 2011 would be in the province of [[Limburg (Netherlands)|Limburg]], site of Queen Beatrix's visit.<ref name=\"ing\" />\n\nAmong the most popular areas for the ''vrijmarkt'' in Amsterdam is the [[Jordaan]] quarter, but the wide Apollolaan in front of the Hilton hotel in southern Amsterdam is gaining in popularity. Children sell their cast-off toys or garments at the [[Vondelpark]], also in southern Amsterdam, and in a spirit of fun passers-by often offer the young sellers more than they are asking for the goods.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.amsterdam.info/queensday/market/\n  | publisher = amsterdam.info\n  | title =Free market on Queen's Day\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> Until 1996, the ''vrijmarkt'' began the evening before and continued for 24&nbsp;hours. This was ended in the hope of gaining a pause in the celebrations so preparations could be made for the daytime activities.<ref name=\"mag\" /> [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]], uniquely among Dutch municipalities, retains the overnight ''vrijmarkt''.<ref name=\"dutchnews\" /> In 2020, people can sell their used goods on an online platform.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Festivities===\n''Koningsdag'' now sees large-scale celebrations, with many concerts and special events in public spaces, particularly in Amsterdam. An outdoor concert is held on Amsterdam's [[Museumplein]], where as many as 800,000&nbsp;people may gather. To aid visitors in returning home by train after the festivities outdoor events must end by 20:00, and the Museumplein show by 21:00.<ref name=\"dutchnews\" /> The city centre is closed to cars, and no trams ride in the heart of the city; people are urged to avoid [[Amsterdam Centraal railway station]] and use other stations if possible from their direction. International trains that normally begin or terminate at Amsterdam Centraal are instead directed to a suburban stop.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.amsterdam.info/queensday/transportation/\n  | publisher = amsterdam.info\n  | title =Transportation during the Queen's Day\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Leaf - Koninginnenach 2008.jpg|thumb|A concert given by the Dutch band [[Leaf (Dutch band)|Leaf]] in [[The Hague]] during ''Koninginnenacht'' in 2008]]\n[[File:DirkvdM koninginnedag 3.jpg|thumb|Revellers dressed in orange in Amsterdam, ''Koninginnedag'' 2007]]\n\nIn recent years parties and concerts have been held the evening before ''Koningsdag''. Until 2013, nightclubs across the Netherlands organised special events for what became known as ''Koninginnenacht'' (Queen's Night).<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.amsterdam.info/queensday\n  | publisher = amsterdam.info\n  | title = Queen's Day in Amsterdam\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> Many young people celebrate in the streets and squares (and in Amsterdam, the canals as well) throughout the night, and after all-night partying join the crowds at the ''vrijmarkt''.<ref name=\"nick\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Thompson\n  | first = Nick\n  | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/04/22/netherlands.queens.day/?hpt=C2 | publisher = [[CNN]]\n  | date = 25 April 2011\n  | title = Queen's Day: Go Dutch for an alternative royal celebration\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>\n{{Anchor|2009 Apeldoorn car accident}}\n\nWhile King's Day celebrations take place throughout the Netherlands, Amsterdam is a popular destination for many revellers. Often the city's 850,000 residents are joined by up to 1 million visitors. In recent years Amsterdam authorities have taken some measures to try to stem the flow of visitors as the city became too crowded.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.dutchamsterdam.nl/2310-amsterdam-says-new-approach-to-queens-day-successful\n  | publisher = dutchamsterdam.nl\n  | title = Amsterdam says new approach to Queen's Day successful\n  | accessdate = 26 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThose taking part in ''Koningsdag'' commonly dye their hair orange or wear orange clothing in honour of the [[House of Orange-Nassau]], which rules over the Netherlands. Orange-coloured drinks are also popular.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =http://www.amsterdam.info/queensday/tradition/\n  | publisher = amsterdam.info\n  | title =Tradition of Queen's Day in Holland\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref> This colour choice is sometimes dubbed \"orange madness\", or in Dutch, ''[[oranjegekte]]''.<ref name=\"nick\" /> A local Orange Committee member said of ''Koninginnedag'' in 2011:\n\n<blockquote>Friendships\u2014and community\u2014will be formed. For me that's really what Queen's Day is all about. It's not an outburst of patriotism, it's not even about the popularity of the royal family. It's about a sense of belonging. For one day, everybody is the same in Holland. Bright orange and barmy.<ref name=\"plan\" /></blockquote>\n\nChildren celebrate with a variety of games including ''koekhappen'' (in which they catch spice cake dangling from a string in their mouths) and ''spijker poepen'' (in which they tie string around their waist a nail dangling at one end, which they attempt to lower into a glass bottle).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/04/22/netherlands.queens.day/|title=Queen's Day: Go Dutch for an alternative royal celebration - CNN.com|last=Thompson|first=Nick|date=25 April 2011|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Honours===\n''Koningsdag'' is an opportunity for the monarch to honour citizens for their service to the Netherlands. In 2011, Queen Beatrix issued an honours list noting the work of 3,357&nbsp;people, most of whom became members of the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]].<ref>{{Cite news\n  | url = http://www.rnw.nl/english/article/dutch-queen\u2019s-day-honours-list\n  | publisher =Radio Netherlands Worldwide\n  | date = 29 April 2011\n  | title =Dutch Queen's Day honours list\n  | accessdate = 1 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Observance in Dutch territories outside Europe==\n''Koningsdag'' is also celebrated in [[Aruba]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]], and [[Sint Maarten]], constituent countries of the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]].<ref name=\"nick\" /> It is less widely celebrated on the Caribbean island of [[Bonaire]], also a part of the Kingdom, where the local celebration of Dia di Rincon (held on 30 April) is more popular.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title = Dia di Rincon populairder dan Koninginnedag op Bonaire\n  | publisher = Radio Netherlands Worldwide (Caribbean)\n  | date = 2 May 2011\n  | url = http://www.rnw.nl/caribiana/article/dia-di-rincon-populairder-dan-koninginnedag-op-bonaire\n  | accessdate = 3 May 2011|language=nl}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Koningsdag}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Koninginnedag}}\n\n{{Public holidays in the Netherlands}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:April observances]]\n[[Category:Dutch monarchy]]\n[[Category:Dutch society]]\n[[Category:Dutch words and phrases]]\n[[Category:National days]]\n[[Category:National holidays]]\n[[Category:Birthdays of heads of state]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Annual events in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Spring (season) events in the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Ishurio19", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWillem-Alexander", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koningsdag"}
